          "body": "The chapter opens with eight verses of courtroom and community ethics that function as the social embodiment of the Decalogue's ninth commandment ('You shall not bear false witness,' 20:16). The commands are concrete and sequential: don't spread false reports; don't follow the crowd into evil; don't show partiality to the poor in a dispute; return your enemy's wandering animal; help your enemy's donkey when it collapses; don't pervert the justice of the needy; stay far from a false charge; don't take bribes; don't oppress strangers. What strikes the reader immediately is the range of the chapter's concern — it protects the rich from a mob (v. 2), the poor from their advocates' corruption (v. 3), and even a personal enemy from a neighbor's convenient indifference (vv. 4-5). Justice in this chapter is not a sentiment; it is a specific set of behaviors required of everyone who testifies, judges, or encounters another person's need. The motive clause of verse 9 is the chapter's ethical fulcrum: 'You know the feelings of a stranger, for you also were strangers in Egypt.' Israel's social ethics are grounded in their redemptive identity. They were once the oppressed foreigner; they must not become the oppressor."
